rris]]\n[[Category:Albums involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Rockfield Studios]]\n[[Category:Brit Award for British Album of the Year]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Album by Oasis}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = (What's the Story) Morning Glory?\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]\n| cover = Oasis - (What's The Story) Morning Glory album cover.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1995|10|2|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = March\u2013June 1995\n| studio     = [[Rockfield Studios]]<br />([[Monmouth]], Wales)\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Partridge|first1=Kenneth|title=Oasis' 'Definitely Maybe' at 20: Classic Track-by-Track Album Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/album-review/6236457/oasis-definitely-maybe-at-20-classic-track-by-track-album|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=17 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107220517/http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/album-review/6236457/oasis-definitely-maybe-at-20-classic-track-by-track-album|archivedate=7 November 2016|date=29 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|last1=Comaratta|first1=Len|title=Oasis \u2013 Definitely Maybe [Reissue]|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/05/album-review-oasis-definitely-maybe-20th-anniversary-reissue/|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=17 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206140449/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/05/album-review-oasis-definitely-maybe-20th-anniversary-reissue/|archivedate=6 December 2016|date=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1834836/whats-the-story-morning-glory-turns-20/franchises/the-anniversary/|title=(What's the Story) Morning Glory? Turns 20|date=2015-10-02}}</ref>|[[Britpop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/oasis-album-whats-the-story-morning-glory-20-things-you-never-knew-about-the-britpop-record-on-its-a6676826.html|title=(What's the Story) Morning Glory? Is 20 years old today|date=2015-10-02}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 50:06\n| label      = [[Creation Records|Creation]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Owen Morris]]|[[Noel Gallagher]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Definitely Maybe]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = (What's the Story) Morning Glory?\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Some Might Say]]\n | single1date = 24 April 1995\n | single2     = [[Roll with It (Oasis song)|Roll with It]]\n | single2date = 14 August 1995\n | single3     = [[Morning Glory (Oasis song)|Morning Glory]]\n | single3date = 18 September 1995\n | single4     = [[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\n | single4date = 30 October 1995\n | single5     = [[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\n | single5date = 19 February 1996\n | single6     = [[Champagne Supernova]]\n | single6date = 13 May 1996\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?''''' is the second studio album by English [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]. Released on 2 October 1995 by [[Creation Records]], it was produced by [[Owen Morris]] and the group's guitarist and main songwriter [[Noel Gallagher]]. The structure and arrangement style of the album were a significant departure from the group's previous album ''[[Definitely Maybe]]'' (1994). Gallagher's compositions were more focused in [[ballad]]ry and placed more emphasis on \"huge\" choruses,<ref name=\"oasis-recordinginfo.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oasis-recordinginfo.co.uk/?page_id=247|title=Owen Morris on producing Morning Glory|work=oasis-recordinginfo.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219023717/http://www.oasis-recordinginfo.co.uk/?page_id=247|archivedate=19 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with the string arrangements and more varied instrumentation contrasting with the rawness of the group's debut album. ''Morning Glory'' was the group's first album with drummer [[Alan White (Oasis drummer)|Alan White]], who replaced [[Tony McCarroll]].\n\nThe record propelled Oasis from being a [[crossover (music)|crossover]] [[Independent music|indie]] act to a worldwide rock phenomenon, and is seen by critics as a significant record in the timeline of British indie music.<ref name=\"Seven Ages of Rock, What the World is Waiting For\">Seven Ages of Rock: What the World is Waiting For</ref> ''Morning Glory'' sold a record-breaking 347,000 copies in its first week, spent 10 weeks at No. 1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], and reached No. 4 on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], making it the band's most commercially successful release. Singles from the album were successful in Britain, America, and Australia: \"[[Some Might Say]]\" and \"[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\" reached No. 1 in the UK, while \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\" and \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" reached No. 1 on the [[Alternative Songs|US Modern Rock Tracks]] chart, with the latter also topping the Australian and New Zealand singles charts.<ref>{{cite web|first=Steffen|last=Hung |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Oasis&titel=Wonderwall&cat=s |title=Oasis&nbsp;\u2014 Wonderwall |website=australian-charts.com |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1996 Brit Awards]], the album won Best British Album. Over several months in 1995 and 1996, the band performed an extensive world tour in support of the album. Among the most notable of these concerts were back-to-back nights at [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre|Earls Court]] in London in November 1995, which were the biggest ever indoor gigs in Europe at the time. They also performed two \"homecoming\" gigs at [[Maine Road]] in Manchester in April 1996. In August of that year, the band played to 80,000 people over two nights at [[Balloch Country Park]] in Scotland. A week later, they held what is arguably their most famous concert when they played two consecutive nights at [[Knebworth House|Knebworth]] to a combined crowd of 250,000 people{{emdash}}for the Knebworth performance, it is believed that approximately 2.5 million people (an estimated 4.4% of the entire UK population at the time) applied for tickets.\n\nAlthough a commercial success, the record initially received lukewarm reviews from mainstream critics; many reviewers deemed it inferior to ''Definitely Maybe'', with the songwriting and production particular points of criticism. However, critical opinion towards the album completely reversed in the ensuing years, and it is now generally considered a seminal record of both the [[Britpop]] era and the 1990s in general, as well as appearing on several lists of the greatest albums in rock music. At the [[2010 Brit Awards]], ''Morning Glory'' was named the greatest British album since 1980.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8517579.stm|title=Lady Gaga wins Brit Awards triple|date=16 February 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> It has sold over 22 million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/06/noel-gallagher-oasis|title=Interview: Noel Gallagher talks Oasis past and present|date=2008-12-06|work=The Guardian}}</ref> As of October 2018, it is the UK's [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|fifth best-selling album]] and third best-selling studio album of all time, having sold over 4.94 million copies,<ref name=\"UK sales\">{{cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/uk-s-60-biggest-selling-albums-of-all-time-revealed/065239|title=UK's 60 Biggest Selling Albums of All Time|last=Gumble|first=Daniel|date=5 July 2016|work=[[Music Week]]|publisher=Intent Media|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> and was also the [[List of best-selling albums of the 1990s in the United Kingdom|UK's best-selling album of the 1990s]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn May 1995, in the wake of the critical and commercial success of their 1994 debut album, ''[[Definitely Maybe]]'', Oasis began recording ''Morning Glory'' at [[Rockfield Studios]] in [[Wales]], with [[Owen Morris]] and [[Noel Gallagher]] producing.<ref name=MOJO>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=AVQbF9lTBwgC&pg=PA622#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Mojo Collection |publisher=Canongate Books|date= 1 November 2007 |accessdate=11 January 2012 |isbn= 978-1-84767-643-6}}</ref> By the time they had finished in June 1995, Oasis were on the brink of becoming one of the most popular bands in the UK; the August 1995 [[Battle of Britpop]] incident in which Oasis and [[Blur (band)|Blur]] had a chart battle over their respective singles \"[[Roll with It (Oasis song)|Roll with It]]\" and \"[[Country House (song)|Country House]]\" would propel them to mainstream awareness.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">\n{{cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/aug/12/pulp.popandrock\n|title=Remember the first time\n|department=Music\n|work=The Guardian\n|first=John\n|last=Harris\n|location=London\n|date=12 August 2005\n|issn=0261-3077\n|oclc=60623878\n|accessdate=9 January 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=HYUifI9rdsoC&pg=PA232#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Revolution Rock: The Albums Which Defined Two Ages|page=232 |first=Amy  |last=Britton| publisher=AuthorHouse |date= Nov 2011 |accessdate=9 January 2012 |isbn= 978-1-4678-8711-3}}</ref>\n\nDespite the friction between the Gallagher brothers, Owen Morris reflected in 2010 that: \"The sessions were the best, easiest, least fraught, most happily creative time I've ever had in a recording studio. I believe people can feel and hear when music is dishonest and motivated by the wrong reasons. ''Morning Glory'', for all its imperfection and flaws, is dripping with love and happiness.\"<ref name=\"oasis-recordinginfo.co.uk\"/> [[Paul Weller]] joined them in the studio and provided lead guitar and backing vocals for \"Champagne Supernova\",<ref name=Weller>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=p5UCtnT7v-IC&pg=PA238#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Paul Weller: my ever changing moods |first=John |last= Reed |page=238|publisher=Music Sales Group|year= 2005 |accessdate=12 January 2012 |isbn= 978-1-84449-491-0}}</ref> and harmonica for the two untitled tracks known as \"The Swamp Song\".<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=p5UCtnT7v-IC&pg=PA298#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Paul Weller: my ever changing moods |first=John |last= Reed |page=298|publisher=Music Sales Group|year= 2005 |accessdate=12 January 2012 |isbn= 978-1-84449-491-0}}</ref>  Noel wrote the last song for the album, \"Cast No Shadow\", on the train as he returned to the studio.<ref name=MOJO/>\n\nMorris claimed the album was recorded in 15 days, at a pace of one song a day.<ref name=\"owen morris\">{{cite web|url=http://owenmorris.net/oasis/|title=The Rise and Fall of Me Recording Oasis|last=Morris|first=Owen|date=|website=owenmorris.net|access-date=24 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112003701/http://owenmorris.net/oasis/|archivedate=12 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"Some Might Say\" proved problematic to record: the backing track was recorded in one take after Noel Gallagher and Morris drunkenly listened to the demo and decided the new version was played too fast, and Noel woke the rest of the band to re-record it. The backing track was faster than intended, with what Morris described as \"a really bad speed up during the first three bars of the first chorus\", but the take had to be used because those involved were impressed with Liam's vocals, and Morris had to mix the track three times, using delay and other processing to hide the mistakes.<ref name=\"owen morris\" /> When the album was finished, Morris said it would \"wipe the field with any competition&nbsp;... It's astonishing. It's the ''[[Never Mind the Bollocks, Here's the Sex Pistols|Bollocks]]'' for this decade.\"<ref>Harris, p. 227</ref> [[Creation Records]] boss [[Alan McGee]] was similarly enthused, saying that \"You just cannot slag this record. It's gonna speak to real, working class lads in a way that a [[Suede (band)|Suede]] or [[Radiohead]] could only dream of doing.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ribbet|first=Paul|date=19 June 1995|title=The making of Creation |magazine=[[The Big Issue]]|issue=135}}</ref> The title ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' was inspired by Noel's friend Melissa Lim answering the phone with said phrase, which is itself derived from a line of ''[[Bye Bye Birdie (song)|Bye Bye Birdie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/movies/article/Major-player-in-Oasis-story-emerges-in-wake-of-10630846.php|title=Major player in Oasis story emerges in wake of \u2018Supersonic\u2019 doc|work=San Francisco Chronicle|author=Vaziri, Aidin|date=23 November 2016|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe brickwall [[audio mastering|mastering]] technique utilised during the recording of the album has led to some journalists claiming that it was responsible for initiating the [[loudness war]], as its heavy use of [[dynamic range compression|compression]], first widely used by Morris on ''Definitely Maybe'', was leaps and bounds beyond what any other album up until then had attempted. Music journalist Nick Southall, who has written extensively on the loudness war, commented, \"If there's a [[jump the shark|jump-the-shark]] moment as far as CD mastering goes then it's probably Oasis.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/imperfect-sound-forever.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330012544/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/imperfect-sound-forever.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 March 2018 |title=Imperfect Sound Forever \u2013 Stylus Magazine |website=stylusmagazine.com |accessdate=7 June 2017 }}</ref> In ''Britpop and the English Music Tradition'' Andy Bennet and John Stratton noted that as a result of this technique \"the songs were especially loud. [Liam] Gallagher's voice is foregrounded to the point that it appears to grow out of the mixes of the songs, exposing itself to execute a pseudo-live quality.\"<ref>Stratton; Bennet, p. 149</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n[[John Harris (critic)|John Harris]] commented in his music history ''Britpop!: Cool Britannia and the Spectacular Demise of English Rock'' that much of the music on ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' seemed to be \"little more inspired than a string of musical hand-me-downs\". Among the musical cues Harris noted on the album were [[Gary Glitter]]'s \"[[Hello, Hello, I'm Back Again]]\" (\"Hello\", Glitter was an influence on Britpop), the theme to the 1970s children's programme ''[[You and Me (UK TV series)|You and Me]]'' and [[The Beatles]]' \"[[While My Guitar Gently Weeps]]\" (\"She's Electric\"), and the influence of [[R.E.M.]]'s \"[[The One I Love (R.E.M. song)|The One I Love]]\" on \"Morning Glory\". One song, \"Step Out\", bore such a close resemblance to the song \"[[Uptight (Everything's Alright)]]\" by [[Stevie Wonder]] that it was removed from the album shortly before release due to the threat of legal action.<ref name=\"Harris, p. 253\u201354\">Harris, p.&nbsp;253\u201354</ref> In ''Britpop&nbsp;...'', Bennet and Stratton analysed Liam Gallagher's vocal style in significant detail, stressing its importance to the songs of the album; \"[Liam's] Mancunian accent blends into a register and timbre that works the gestural contours of the melody and lyrics.\" Bennet and Stratton went on to conclude that Liam's 'over-personalized' style on songs such as \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" resulted in \"a beautiful sense of sentimentality that bespeaks the despondency of a generation. This occurs through the narrative structure of the song, vocal production, and the conventions of the singer's cultural context.\"<ref>Stratton; Bennet, p.&nbsp;148\u201349</ref>\n\nNoel Gallagher summed up his own perspective on the album's aesthetic in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1995; \"Whilst [''Definitely Maybe''] is about dreaming of being a pop star in a band, ''What's the Story'' is about actually ''being'' a pop star in a band.\"<ref>[http://www.avclub.com/articles/part-8-1997-the-ballad-of-oasis-and-radiohead,50557/ The AV Club: Alternative Nation \u2013 Part 8: ''The Ballad of Oasis and Radiohead'']</ref> The album has a notable anthemic theme to its songs, differing from the rawness and edged rock of ''Definitely Maybe''. The use of string arrangements and more varied instrumentation in songs such as \"Don't Look Back in Anger\" and \"Champagne Supernova\" was a significant departure from the band's debut. This style had first been implemented by the band on their fifth single, \"[[Whatever (Oasis song)|Whatever]]\", released in December 1994. It was produced in conjunction with the London Symphony Orchestra, resulting in a much more pop-oriented and mellower sound; this would be the template that would come to define many of the songs on ''What's the Story''.<ref name = \"BBC sevenages\">{{BBC Online|id=music/sevenages/|title='Seven Ages'}}</ref> In the BBC documentary ''[[Seven Ages of Rock]]'', former NME chief editor Steve Sutherland noted that \"with ''Morning Glory'', [Noel] began to take seriously the notion of being the voice of a generation\".<ref name= \"BBC sevenages\"/>\n\n==Cover==\nThe cover is a picture of two men passing each other on [[Berwick Street]] in London. The two men are London DJ [[Sean Rowley]] and album sleeve designer [[Brian Cannon]] (back to the camera).  The album's producer Owen Morris can be seen in the background, on the left footpath, holding the album's master tape in front of his face.<ref name=\"fotostrasse.com\">{{cite web|url=http://fotostrasse.com/whats-story-morning-glory-20-years-later/|title=Fotostrasse presents What's The Story? Morning Glory|work=Fotostrasse|date=2016-06-25}}</ref>  The location was chosen because the street was a popular location for record shops at the time.<ref name=\"fotostrasse.com\"/> The cover cost \u00a325,000 to produce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigissue.com/features/interviews/4450/what-s-the-story-morning-glory-the-true-story-behind-the-cover|title=(What's The Story) Morning Glory: The true story behind the cover - The Big Issue|date=1 October 2014|website=bigissue.com|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nWhile \"[[Some Might Say]]\", a number one hit, had been released in April, the single chosen to precede the album's release was \"[[Roll with It (Oasis song)|Roll with It]]\", planned for release on 14 August, six weeks before the album was due to hit the shelves. This was an unorthodox method for the time, contrasting the standard industry procedure of releasing the lead single three weeks before its parent album.<ref>Harris, p. 250: \"Blur had assumed that Oasis would follow standard music business protocol, releasing a single three weeks before the album.\"</ref> [[Blur (band)|Blur]]'s management had become worried that this would hinder the chances of the group's forthcoming \"[[Country House (song)|Country House]]\" single reaching number one the following week. As a reaction, [[Food Records]] pushed the release of \"Country House\" back a week and thus started what became known as '[[The Battle of Britpop]]'.\n\nThe event triggered an unprecedented amount of exposure for both bands in national newspapers and on television news bulletins, supposedly symbolising the battle between the middle class of the south and the working class of the north. In the midst of the battle a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' newspaper headline proclaimed \"Working Class Heroes Lead Art School Trendies\". In the event \"Country House\" outsold \"Roll with It\" by 54,000, and topped the singles chart for a fortnight. Overall singles sales that week were up by 41 percent.<ref>Harris, p.&nbsp;229\u2013235</ref> In 2005, John Harris reflected on the importance of the event in popularising Britpop; \"(as) Blur's \"Country House\" raced Oasis' \"Roll with It\" to the top of the charts, just about every voice in the media felt compelled to express an opinion on the freshly inaugurated age of Britpop.\"<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/>\n\nDuring a promotional interview in September, the month before the album was released, Noel spoke about the rivalry with [[Damon Albarn]] and [[Alex James (musician)|Alex James]] from Blur, and was quoted in the 17 September edition of ''[[The Observer]]'' saying he hoped \"the pair of them would catch [[AIDS]] and die because I fucking hate them two.\"<ref name=\"Harris, p. 250\">Harris, p. 250</ref> Although Noel recanted and said that AIDS is no laughing matter,<ref name=\"apology\">{{cite web | author=Titorenko, Mark|date=19 February 1996 | title=Noel's AIDS comment | publisher=The Oasis Archive | url=http://ireland.iol.ie/~kglennon/paper/bandi.htm| accessdate=17 January 2006}} (scroll down to section 3.5)</ref> the quote caused a storm of controversy, with Noel having to write a letter of apology; he later confessed that \"my whole world came crashing down in on me then\".<ref name=\"Harris, p. 250\"/> However, in an interview with ''The Guardian'' in 2005, Blur's guitarist [[Graham Coxon]] explained that he bore no malice towards Oasis. \"At least they were outright about it. They weren't pretending to like us and then slagging us off, which is what we'd been used to. In that way, I quite appreciated them.\"<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 2 October 2018, to mark the 23rd anniversary of the album release, a new lyric video, described as being \"loaded with psychedelic imagery\", was published on the band's YouTube VEVO channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/oasis-unveil-new-lyric-video-shes-electric-2385754#MjylkVUuoic6Klkf.99|title=Oasis unveil new lyric video for 'She's Electric' - NME|date=2 October 2018|publisher=nme.com|accessdate=23 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{youtube|h9JZWhjQDvc|Oasis - She's Electric (Lyric Video)}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' was released on 2 October 1995. The album sold quickly; the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' reported the day after release that central London [[HMV]] stores were selling copies of the album at a rate of two per minute. At the end of the first week of sales, the album had sold a record-breaking 347,000 copies, making it (at the time) the second-fastest-selling album in British history, behind [[Michael Jackson]]'s ''[[Bad (album)|Bad]]''. After initially entering the UK charts at number one, it hovered around the top three for the rest of the year before initiating a six-week stay at the top in mid January, followed by a further three weeks at number one in March. In total, the album did not leave the top three for an astonishing seven months.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/%28What%27s%20The%20Story%29%20Morning%20Glory%3F|title=ChartArchive - The Chart Archive|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fourth single from the album, \"Wonderwall\", hit the top ten in several countries, including stays at number one in Australia and New Zealand and achieving a peak of number eight in the United States, the album began to enjoy prolonged international success. Eventually the album had a five-week run at the top of the Australian albums chart and an eight-week run at the top of the New Zealand albums chart before topping charts in Canada, Ireland, Sweden and Switzerland. The album was also making significant waves in the US market, thanks in part to the success of the \"Wonderwall\" and \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\" singles on American modern rock radio. Both songs reached number one on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Chart]] and stayed there for ten and five weeks respectively. By early 1996, ''What's the Story'' was selling 200,000 copies a week, eventually peaking at number four and being certified four times platinum by the end of the year for shipments of over four million units.<ref>Harris, p. 261</ref>\n\n==Tour==\n{{Main|(What's the Story) Morning Glory? Tour}}\n\nThe band embarked on what would become a 103 show world tour in support of the album over a period of several months in 1995 and 1996. The tour started on 22 June 1995 with a pre-Glastonbury festival warm-up gig at the 1,400 capacity Bath Pavilion,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bathpavilion.org/hire-bath-pavilion |title=Bath Pavilion |website=bathpavilion.org |year=2012 |accessdate=8 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120225041901/http://www.bathpavilion.org/hire-bath-pavilion |archivedate=25 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which featured the debut of new drummer Alan White and several new songs off the album, and ended on 4 December 1996 at the 11,800 capacity Mayo Civic Centre in Rochester, Minnesota, USA,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mayociviccenter.com/facilities/Auditorium/index.aspx |title=Mayo Civic Center : Facilities  |website=mayociviccenter.com |year=2012 |accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref> and included concerts at [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre|Earls Court]] in November 1995 and [[Cardiff International Arena]] in March 1996.<ref name=harris>Harris, John. Britpop!: Cool Britannia and the Spectacular Demise of English Rock. Da Capo Press, 2004. {{ISBN|0-306-81367-X}}</ref> The tour had many disruptions and cancellations due to Noel twice walking out of the group, and Liam pulling out of a US leg.<ref name=harris />\n\nIn September 1995, bass player [[Paul McGuigan (musician)|Paul McGuigan]] walked out on the group after he was subjected to a flurry of verbal abuse from Liam while doing interviews in Paris. 'Guigsy' cited nervous exhaustion as the reason for his departure.<ref name=\"Harris, p. 255\">Harris, p. 255</ref> [[Scott McLeod (bassist)|Scott Mcleod]] of The Ya-Yas was brought in as his replacement; though, despite playing a string of gigs with the band and appearing in the video for the \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" single, Mcleod was unable to adapt to the frenetic celebrity lifestyle, duly returning to Manchester halfway through an American promotional tour for the album.<ref name=\"Harris, p. 255\"/> The band played a few dates, including an appearance on ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', as a four piece, before McGuigan was convinced to return for the group's [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre|Earls Court]] shows in early November.<ref name=\"Harris, p. 255\"/> When the band broke up for a brief time in late 1996, several US tour dates and the entire Australia and New Zealand leg had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itnsource.com/shotlist//ITN/1996/09/12/BSP120996008/?s=Oasis+band+1994&st=0&pn=2 |title=Oasis: Abandoned US Tour Fuels Rumours of Split |accessdate=9 January 2011 |website=Itn Source |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719185651/http://www.itnsource.com/shotlist//RTV/2007/02/16/RTV248507/ |archivedate=19 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAs the band began to reach the peak of their popularity, several large open-air concerts were organized in the UK during 1996, including two gigs at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] football stadium [[Maine Road]], two nights at [[Loch Lomond]] in Scotland, and two nights at [[Concerts at Knebworth House|Knebworth House]] in front of a record 125,000 people each night; an event that would come to be acknowledged as the height of the Britpop phenomenon, with one journalist commenting; \"(Knebworth) could be seen as the last great Britpop performance; nothing after would match its scale.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/indie/oasis-at-knebworth/|title=BBC - Seven Ages of Rock - Events - Oasis At Knebworth|author=BBC|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At the time, the concerts were the biggest gigs ever held for a single band on UK soil, and to date remain the largest demand ever for a British concert; with reportedly over 2.5 million applications for tickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/23794|title=Oasis mark Knebworth anniversary|author=NME.COM|work=NME.COM|date=2006-08-02}}</ref> The Earl's Court and Maine Road gigs were filmed and later released as the Oasis VHS/DVD ''[[...There and Then]]''.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/whats-the-story-morning-glory-mw0000176500|title=(What's the Story) Morning Glory?&nbsp;\u2013 Oasis|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=25 September 2009|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|isbn=978-0-85712-595-8|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1995/10/06/whats-story-morning-glory|title=(What's the Story) Morning Glory?|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=6 October 1995|accessdate=25 September 2009|last=Flaherty|first=Mike}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news|title=CD of the week: (the inevitable) Oasis|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 September 1995|last=Sullivan|first=Caroline}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-10-01/entertainment/ca-51934_1_morning-glory|title=Oasis; \"(What's the Story) Morning Glory?\", Epic|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1 October 1995|accessdate=19 October 2015|last=Hilburn|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Hilburn}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 7/10<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 8.9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19771-oasis-whats-the-story-morning-glory/|title=Oasis: (What's the Story) Morning Glory?|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=27 January 2016|last=Berman|first=Stuart}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"rs\"/>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|5|5}}{{sfn|Sheffield|2004|p=598}}\n| rev10 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev10score = 4/5<ref>{{cite journal|title=Star Trip II: The Search For Rock|journal=[[Select (magazine)|Select]]|issue=65|date=November 1995|last=Harrison|first=Andrew|pages=98\u201399}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' was released to lukewarm reviews from the mainstream music press. Many contemporary reviewers expressed disappointment at the album's perceived inferiority to ''Definitely Maybe'', taking aim at the 'banal lyrics' and the unoriginal nature of the compositions.<ref name=\"archivedmusicpress.files.wordpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://archivedmusicpress.files.wordpress.com/2009/07/david-stubbs-reviews-whats-the-story-morning-glory-30th-september-1995.jpg|title=Tale Ending?|work=[[Melody Maker]]|date=30 September 1995|accessdate=15 April 2014|last=Stubbs|first=David}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/album-review-oasis-whats-the-story-morning-glory-creation-cre-cd-189-1603376.html|title=Album Review: Oasis (What's the Story) Morning Glory Creation CRE CD|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 September 1995|accessdate=15 April 2014|last=Gill|first=Andy}}</ref> David Cavanagh of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine said of the lyrics \"They scan; they fill a hole; end of story. They [say] nothing much about anything.\"<ref name=\"Harris, p. 254\">Harris, p. 254</ref> Andy Gill of ''[[The Independent]]'' commented that \"She's Electric\" is \"laddism of a tiresomely generic kind\", while \"Roll with It\" is \"drab and chummy\".<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> Perhaps the most damning review came from David Stubbs of the now-defunct ''[[Melody Maker]]''. Despite stating that \"Some Might Say\" was \"the best single of the year\", Stubbs went on to be critical of the album as a whole; \"''What's the Story'' [sounds] laboured and lazy. On this evidence, Oasis are a limited band&nbsp;... they sound knackered.\"<ref name=\"archivedmusicpress.files.wordpress.com\"/><ref name=\"Harris, p. 254\" />\n\nIn a positive review, ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s Jon Weiderhorn wrote that \"''What's the Story'' is more than a natural progression, it's a bold leap forward that displays significant musical and personal growth.\" Weiderhorn went on to note that the 'stormy' relationship between Liam and Noel proved to be one of the album's strengths; \"tension and instability have been inherent traits of great rock teams&nbsp;... for Oasis, the addition of shared genes gives their songs extra impact and dimension.\"<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/whats-the-story-morning-glory-19951019|title=Oasis: (What's the Story) Morning Glory?|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|issue=719|date=19 October 1995|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' said that the album shows Oasis pursuing \"an altogether different direction; away from the conscience-free overloaded hedonism towards an understanding of its consequences\".<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001047reviews.html |title=Oasis \u2013 (What's The Story) Morning Glory? |journal=[[NME]] |location=London |page=52 |date=30 September 1995 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |last=Robinson |first=John |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817190458/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001047reviews.html |archivedate=17 August 2000 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The album finished 10th in the voting for ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s annual [[Pazz & Jop]] critics' poll.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres95.php|title=The 1995 Pazz & Jop Critics Poll|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=20 February 1996|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''Britpop!'', John Harris concluded that the initial negative reviews of the time missed the album's universal strengths. \"Those who fussed about the music's more artful aspects were missing the point. The fact that [Noel's] songs contained so many musical echoes seemed to couch the album in an air of homely reassurance.\" Harris believed that the \"ordinary\" nature of some of the album's songs \"turned out to be part of its deeply populist appeal\".<ref name=\"Harris, p. 254\" /> [[Rob Sheffield]], writing in ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (2004), called the album \"a triumph, full of bluster and bravado but also moments of surprising tenderness\".{{sfn|Sheffield|2004|p=598}} [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic in his retrospective review and gave it a two-star honourable mention,{{sfn|Christgau|2000|p=231}} indicating a \"likable effort that consumers attuned to its overriding aesthetic or individual vision may well enjoy.\"{{sfn|Christgau|2000|p=xvi}} He cited \"She's Electric\" and \"Roll with It\" as highlights and quipped \"give them credit for wanting it all\u2014and (yet another Beatles connection!) playing guitars\".{{sfn|Christgau|2000|p=231}}\n\n==Legacy==\n''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' is considered a seminal record of the [[Britpop]] era and one of the best albums of the nineties,<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/rolling-stone-readers-pick-the-top-10-albums-of-the-nineties-20110216/5-oasis-whats-the-story-morning-glory-0122161|title=5. Oasis \u2013 '(What's The Story) Morning Glory?'|work=Rolling Stone|date=2011-02-16}}</ref> and it appears in several charts as one of the greatest albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.besteveralbums.com/thechart.php?a=188#rankings |title=(What's the Story) Morning Glory? (album) by Oasis : Best Ever Albums  |website=besteveralbums.com |year=2012 |accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref> In 2010, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that \"the album is a triumph, full of bluster, bravado and surprising tenderness. ''Morning Glory'' capped a true golden age for Britpop.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/oasis/albumguide|title=Rolling Stone Album Guide: Morning Glory|website=rollingstone.com|accessdate=7 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226124437/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/oasis/albumguide|archive-date=26 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The magazine ranked the album at 378 on its 2012 list of \"[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/whats-the-story-morning-glory-oasis-19691231|title=500 Greatest Albums: (What's the Story) Morning Glory?|website=rollingstone.com|accessdate=7 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530070857/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/whats-the-story-morning-glory-oasis-19691231|archive-date=30 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album's enduring popularity within the UK was reflected when it won the BRITs Album of 30 years at the [[2010 BRIT Awards]]. The award was voted by the public to decide the greatest 'Best Album' winner in the history of the BRIT Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.com/2010/02/16/brits-album-of-30-years/|title=AOL Radio Stations|author=Slacker, Inc.|work=AOL Radio}}</ref>  The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=23 March 2010|publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref> It was voted number 21 in [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=44}}</ref>\n\n''What's the Story'' went on to become the best-selling album of the decade in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/chartalb5.html|title=1990s Albums Chart Archive \u2013 everyHit.com|work=everyhit.com}}</ref> with its fifteen platinum certifications from the [[British Phonographic Industry]]. It was also certified four times platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]]. The fifteen platinum certifications in the UK were the highest ever awarded to a single record until [[Adele]]'s ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]'', released in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx|title=Certified Awards|work=bpi.co.uk}}</ref> The success of the album resulted in Oasis becoming one of the biggest bands in the world, with substantial and considerable press coverage in the mainstream music press and frequent comparisons to [[the Beatles]] in the media.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/> Liam and Noel Gallagher both featured prominently in gossip columns and daily tabloids throughout 1996\u201397.\n\n''What's the Story'' propelled Oasis from being a crossover indie act to a worldwide rock phenomenon after the momentum gained by the critically acclaimed ''Definitely Maybe''. It has been pinpointed by music critics as a significant record in the timeline of British indie music, demonstrating just how far into the mainstream independent music had ventured.<ref name=\"Seven Ages of Rock, What the World is Waiting For\"/> In 2005, John Harris noted the significance of the album and \"Wonderwall\" in particular to Britpop's legacy. \"When (Oasis) released Wonderwall, the rules of British music were decisively changed. From hereon in, the lighter-than-air ballad became obligatory, and the leather-trousers era of rock'n'roll was over.\"<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> The success of the album in Britain resulted in Oasis becoming a cultural ubiquity for a brief period, featuring in tabloid newspapers on an almost daily basis and breaking sales records for live concerts.<ref name=\"Harris, p. 230\">Harris, p. 230</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, while reviewing the most overrated albums of all time, where ''Morning Glory'' ranked number 16, writer Max Easton of [[FasterLouder]] wrote that the album is \"full of anthems for the sake of anthems,\" and that \"they're all variations on only a couple of good ideas.\" He concluded by saying, \"''What's the Story''{{'}}s lasting place in '90s folklore is less about the quality of the album, and more about the celebrity status and faux imagery attached to it.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Easton|first1=Max|title=The Most Overrated Albums Of All Time|url=http://fasterlouder.junkee.com/the-most-overrated-albums-of-all-time/829875/4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121010150/http://fasterlouder.junkee.com/the-most-overrated-albums-of-all-time/829875/4|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2015|website=[[FasterLouder]]|accessdate=10 January 2017|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n===Original release===\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Noel Gallagher]], except where noted\n| title1 = Hello\n| note1 = writers: Noel Gallagher, [[Gary Glitter]], [[Mike Leander]]\n| length1 = 3:21\n| title2 = [[Roll with It (Oasis song)|Roll with It]]\n| length2 = 3:59\n| title3 = [[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]] \n| length3 = 4:18\n| title4 = [[Don't Look Back in Anger]] \n| length4 = 4:48\n| title5 = Hey Now!\n| length5 = 5:41\n| title6 = \n| note6 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 1\"\n| length6 = 0:44\n| title7 = [[Some Might Say]]\n| length7 = 5:29\n| title8 = Cast No Shadow\n| length8 = 4:51\n| title9 = She's Electric\n| length9 = 3:40\n| title10 = [[Morning Glory (Oasis song)|Morning Glory]]\n| length10 = 5:03\n| title11 = \n| note11 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 2\"\n| length11 = 0:39\n| title12 = [[Champagne Supernova]]\n| length12 = 7:27\n}}\n\n===Vinyl version===\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = Hello\n| note1 = Gallagher, Glitter, Leander\n| length1 = 3:21\n| title2 = Roll with It\n| length2 = 3:59\n| title3 = Wonderwall\n| length3 = 4:18\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title1 = Don't Look Back in Anger\n| length1 = 4:48\n| title2 = Hey Now!\n| length2 = 5:41\n| title3 = \n| note3 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 1\"\n| length3 = 0:44\n| title4 = Bonehead's Bank Holiday\n| length4 = 4:03\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side three\n| title1 = Some Might Say\n| length1 = 5:29\n| title2 = Cast No Shadow\n| length2 = 4:51\n| title3 = She's Electric\n| length3 = 3:40\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side four\n| title1 = Morning Glory\n| length1 = 5:03\n| title2 = \n| note2 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 2\"\n| length2 = 0:39\n| title3 = Champagne Supernova\n| length3 = 7:27\n}}\n\n===Singles box set===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = (What's the Story) Morning Glory?\n| type       = box\n| artist     = [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]\n| cover      = Morning Glory (singles box).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 4 November 1996\n| recorded   = 1995\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Britpop]]\n| length     = 81:59\n| label      = [[Creation Records|Creation]]\n| producer   = [[Owen Morris]], [[Noel Gallagher]]\n| chronology = [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] box set\n| prev_title = [[Definitely Maybe#Singles box set|Definitely Maybe]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe '''''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?''''' [[box set]] was released on 4 November 1996, featuring four discs of singles, including B-sides, and one disc of interviews. The album charted at number 24 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/oasis/#albums|title=Featured Artists: Oasis|website=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203012508/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/oasis#albums|archivedate=3 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAll songs written by Noel Gallagher, except \"[[Cum on Feel the Noize]]\" by [[Noddy Holder]] and [[Jim Lea (musician)|Jim Lea]]; \"Step Out\" co-written by [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Henry Cosby]] and [[Sylvia Moy]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = yes\n| all_writing   =\n| headline      = Disc one\n| title1        = Interviews\n| length1       = 18:22\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = yes\n| all_writing   =\n| headline      = Disc two\n| title1        = Some Might Say\n| length1       = 5:29\n| title2        = [[Talk Tonight]]\n| length2       = 4:21\n| title3        = [[Acquiesce]]\n| length3       = 4:25\n| title4        = Headshrinker\n| length4       = 4:38\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = yes\n| all_writing   =\n| headline      = Disc three\n| title1        = Roll with It\n| length1       = 3:59\n| title2        = It's Better People\n| length2       = 3:59\n| title3        = Rockin' Chair\n| length3       = 4:36\n| title4        = [[Live Forever (Oasis song)|Live Forever]]\n| note4         = Live at [[Glastonbury Festival]], 1995\n| length4       = 4:40\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = yes\n| all_writing   =\n| headline      = Disc four\n| title1        = Wonderwall\n| length1       = 4:18\n| title2        = Round Are Way\n| length2       = 5:42\n| title3        = The Swamp Song\n| length3       = 4:15\n| title4        = [[The Masterplan (song)|The Masterplan]]\n| length4       = 5:23\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed     = yes\n| all_writing   =\n| headline      = Disc five\n| title1        = Don't Look Back in Anger\n| length1       = 4:47\n| title2        = Step Out\n| length2       = 3:40\n| title3        = Underneath the Sky\n| length3       = 3:20\n| title4        = [[Cum on Feel the Noize]]\n| length4       = 5:09\n}}\n\n===2014 reissue===\nAs part of a promotional campaign entitled '''Chasing the Sun''', the album was re-released on 29 September 2014. The 3-disc deluxe edition includes remastered versions of the album and its associated b-sides from the four UK singles. Bonus content includes 5 demo tracks, and live choices taken from the band's iconic gigs at Earls Court, Knebworth Park and Maine Road.\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 2014 reissue disc 1: ''(What's the Story) Morning Glory?''\n| all_writing = [[Noel Gallagher]], except where noted\n| title1 = Hello\n| note1 = Noel Gallagher, [[Gary Glitter]], [[Mike Leander]]\n| length1 = 3:21\n| title2 = [[Roll with It (Oasis song)|Roll with It]]\n| length2 = 3:59\n| title3 = [[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]] \n| length3 = 4:18\n| title4 = [[Don't Look Back in Anger]] \n| length4 = 4:48\n| title5 = Hey Now!\n| length5 = 5:41\n| title6 = \n| note6 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 1\"\n| length6 = 0:44\n| title7 = [[Some Might Say]]\n| length7 = 5:29\n| title8 = Cast No Shadow\n| length8 = 4:51\n| title9 = She's Electric\n| length9 = 3:40\n| title10 = [[Morning Glory (Oasis song)|Morning Glory]]\n| length10 = 5:03\n| title11 = \n| note11 = also known as \"The Swamp Song&nbsp;\u2014 Excerpt 2\"\n| length11 = 0:39\n| title12 = [[Champagne Supernova]]\n| length12 = 7:27\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Japanese bonus tracks (SICP-4152)\n| title13 = Hello\n| note13 = [[Demo (music)|Demo]]\n| length13 = 3:15\n| title14 = Wonderwall\n| note14 = Live at [[Knebworth]] Park\n| length14 = 4:07\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2014 reissue disc 2: ''B-Sides''\n| title1 = Talk Tonight\n| length1 = 4:24\n| title2 = Acquiesce\n| length2 = 4:29\n| title3 = Headshrinker\n| length3 = 4:42\n| title4 = It's Better People\n| length4 = 4:01\n| title5 = Rockin' Chair\n| length5 = 4:40\n| title6 = Step Out\n| note6 = [[Henry Cosby]], Noel Gallagher, [[Sylvia Moy]], [[Stevie Wonder]]\n| length6 = 3:45\n| title7 = Underneath the Sky\n| length7 = 3:25\n| title8 = [[Cum On Feel the Noize]]\n| note8 = [[Jim Lea (musician)|Jim Lea]], [[Noddy Holder]]\n| length8 = 5:13\n| title9 = Round Are Way\n| length9 = 5:45\n| title10 = The Swamp Song\n| length10 = 4:23\n| title11 = The Masterplan\n| length11 = 5:26\n| title12 = Bonehead's Bank Holiday\n| length12 = 4:03\n| title13 = Champagne Supernova\n| note13 = [[Brendan Lynch (music producer)|Brendan Lynch]] [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]]\n| length13 = 6:59\n| title14 = [[You've Got to Hide Your Love Away]]\n| note14 = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| length14 = 2:18\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2014 reissue disc 3: ''Rare Tracks''\n| title1 = Acquiesce\n| note1 = live at Earls Court, London on 4 November 1995\n| length1 = 3:55\n| title2 = Some Might Say\n| note2 = demo. Recorded at soundcheck Club Quattro Tokyo, Japan on 14 September 1994\n| length2 = 4:04\n| title3 = Some Might Say\n| note3 = live at Roskilde Festival, Denmark on 30 June 1995\n| length3 = 5:07\n| title4 = She's Electric\n| note4 = demo. Recorded at Mauldeth Road West Studio, Manchester\t\n| length4 = 3:03\n| title5 = Talk Tonight\n| note5 = live at Bath Pavilion on 22 June 1995\n| length5 = 3:43\n| title6 = Rockin' Chair\n| note6 = demo. Recorded at Mauldeth Road West Studio, Manchester\n| length6 = 4:05\n| title7 = Hello\n| note7 = live at Roskilde Festival, Denmark on 30 June 1995\n| length7 = 3:24\n| title8 = Roll with It\n| note8 = live at Roskilde Festival, Denmark on 30 June 1995\n|